# MODD: Memory-Augmented Open-World Detection for Degraded Conditions

> Retrieval-augmented object detection that leverages associative memory to
> bridge the domain gap between clean and degraded visual conditions.

## Overview

MODD uses a frozen **Grounding DINO** open-world detector as the backbone and
adds lightweight trainable modules (~8M params) that retrieve clean-domain
knowledge from an associative memory bank to refine degraded proposals.

**Key idea:** Foundation models produce lower-confidence detections under
degradation. We use this uncertainty signal to trigger memory retrieval,
pulling clean-domain prototypes that refine the degraded features via
cross-attention — without retraining the foundation model.

## Architecture

```
Degraded Image → Frozen G-DINO → Initial Proposals → Confidence Split
                                                         ↓
                                        Low-conf proposals → Proposal Encoder
                                                              → Memory Retrieval (FAISS k-NN)
                                                              → Refinement (Cross-Attention)
                                                              → Refined Detection Head
                                                         ↓
                                              Merge with high-conf → Final Detections
                                                         ↓
                                              Memory Update (EMA) → Memory Bank
```

**5 Core Modules:**
1. **Memory Bank** — FAISS-backed clean-domain feature storage (class prototypes + instance supports)
2. **Proposal Encoder** — Projects G-DINO query features into retrieval space (~1.5M params)
3. **Memory Retrieval** — Cosine k-NN search with learnable temperature
4. **Refinement Module** — 2-layer Transformer decoder with cross-attention (~6M params)
5. **Memory Update** — Online EMA insertion of high-confidence target features

## Project Structure

```
├── configs/          # Hydra YAML configs (model, data, training phases)
├── src/
│   ├── models/       # All 5 modules + G-DINO wrapper + full pipeline
│   ├── data/         # Degradation synthesis + dataset adapters
│   ├── training/     # Losses, trainer, LR schedulers
│   └── utils/        # Hooks, visualization, metrics
├── scripts/          # Memory construction, training, evaluation, demo
└── tests/            # Unit tests for each module
```

## Quick Start

### Install
```bash
pip install -e ".[dev]"
```

### Phase A: Build Memory Bank
```bash
python scripts/build_memory_bank.py \
    --config configs/train/phase_a_memory.yaml \
    --max-images 1000
```

### Phase B: Train Adaptation Modules
```bash
python scripts/train_modules.py \
    --config configs/train/phase_b_modules.yaml
```

### Evaluate
```bash
python scripts/evaluate.py \
    --config configs/data/foggy_cityscapes.yaml \
    --checkpoint outputs/checkpoints/best.ckpt
```

## Hardware Requirements

| Setup | VRAM | Notes |
|:---|:---|:---|
| Inference only | ~8 GB | Frozen G-DINO base + modules |
| Training (Phase B) | ~14-16 GB | With gradient checkpointing + FP16 |
| Recommended | **RTX 3090 (24 GB)** | Comfortable for all phases |

## Degradation Types

| Type | Method | Parameters |
|:---|:---|:---|
| **Haze/Fog** | Koschmieder atmospheric scattering | β ∈ [0.5, 2.0], A ∈ [0.7, 1.0] |
| **Night/Low-light** | Gamma correction + Poisson/Gaussian noise | γ ∈ [2.0, 4.0], σ ∈ [0.01, 0.05] |
| **Combined** | Stochastic composition | Random mix of above |

## Benchmarks

| Dataset | Degradation | Protocol |
|:---|:---|:---|
| Foggy Cityscapes | Synthetic haze | Clean Cityscapes → Foggy |
| RTTS | Real-world haze | COCO → RTTS |
| ExDark | Real-world night | COCO → ExDark |
| BDD100K-night | Real night driving | BDD-day → BDD-night |

